<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-831-055  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 831 055.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 8 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Hacker Morris sentenced. (Robert Tappan Morris)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Computer hackersLegal IssuesCourt CasesComputer Viruses.andO;Person:    Morris, Robert T., Jr. (Discipline).andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>HACKER MORRIS SENTENCED SYRACUSE, NEW YORK, U.S.A., 1990 MAY 4 (NB) -- RobertTappan Morris, convicted on January 22nd for a 1988 infection of thousands ofcomputers with a worm, was sentenced on Friday, May 4th to three yearsprobation, a $10,000 fine and 400 hours of community service.andP;  Under theruling by U.S.andP;  District Judge Howard Munson, Morris will also have to paycosts related to the administration of his probation.andM;Morris, the 24 year-old son of Robert Morris, a chief scientist at theNational Computer Security Center, is the first person to be prosecuted underthe 1986 Computer Fraud and Abuse Act which makes it a felony tointentionally access, without authorization, certain federal computers andcause more than $1,000 in damage.andP;  Under the terms of the law, Morris couldhave been imprisoned for up to five years in prison and been fined up to$250,000.andM;In imposing the sentence, Judge Munson said that he had not been able to findany applicable guidelines to set precedent and was quoted as adding, &quot;Thetotal dollar loss (of the crime) overstates the seriousness of the offense.&quot;andM;Pre-sentencing speculation seemed to focus on a possible short prison termfor Morris with one of his attorneys, Thomas Guidoboni, indicating that,while he would urge Judge Munson to not impose prison time, hisinterpretation of federal sentencing guidelines indicated that Morris couldreceive up to six months in prison.andP;  Guidoboni also had said that his readingof a pre-sentencing report indicated government prosecutors want the judge tofollow federal sentencing guidelines that support a 21- to 27-month prisonterm.andM;At the time of Guidoboni's statement, Douglas Tillett, a spokesman for theU.S.andP;  Justice Department, said the government has not made a recommendation,adding that it was &quot;premature to speculate on what would happen in opencourt.&quot;andM;Morris' conviction was the result of a July 1989 indictment for hisactivities on November 2, 1988 when he released a computer worm, aself-replicating program, into computer networks that serviced university andmilitary research facilities.andP;  The worm infected and shut down an estimated6,000 Unix-based systems attached to the Internet, Arpanet and Milnetnetworks.andP;  Among those installations reporting infection were the NationalAeronautics and Space Administration facility at Moffett Field, Calif., andthe U.S.andP;  Air Force Logistics Command at Wright-Patterson Air Force Base inDayton, Ohio.andM;Morris, a 1988 graduate of Harvard University, committed the action while agraduate student at Cornell University.andP;  He is presently suspended fromCornell until September 1990 and has been living in Cambridge, MA where he isworking as a programmer at Harvard.andM;Commenting on Morris' sentence, Clifford Stoll, author of The Cuckoo's Eggwhich depicts his lengthy tracking down of a hacker accessing these samenetworks for espionage purposes, told Newsbytes, &quot;It seems to me that it is awell-balanced good sentence.andP;  It says 'Look, if you screw up people's work,you must pay! It's not a light sentence.andP;  It'll cost him big bucks, both inthe fine and his large legal fees.andP;  Additionally, he's paying back somethingto the community by his service.andP;  I think it's fair.andP;  A prison sentence wouldhave satisfied none but the vindictive.&quot;andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900505)</TEXT></DOC>